<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-03T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-03T16:00:00-05:00" n="169" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/1751</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                Minister <persName type="to">Reinsch</persName>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-03T16:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 3, 1917, 4 p.m</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your February 26, 11 p.m. John Jay Abbott, Vice President, Continental
                            and Commercial Bank, Chicago, will sail on <hi rend="italic">Empress of
                                Asia</hi> for China, March 15, with full powers to conduct
                            negotiations. He will be accompanied by one other bank official and go
                            from Yokohama by rail and be due in Peking about April. Advise Chinese
                            Government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>